article.headline: Palmer's double-double paces Connecticut
article.linkText: Sun rally past Mystics for third victory in a row
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Wendy Palmer made sure the Connecticut Sun won
in their first road game of the year Friday night.

Palmer had 21 points and 10 rebounds for her second
double-double of the season, leading the Sun to a 72-63 win over
the Washington Mystics.

Lindsay Whalen added a career-high 13 points for the Sun (3-2),
who won their third straight.

Taj McWilliams-Franklin finished with 12 points and nine
rebounds and Katie Douglas added 10 points for Connecticut, which
had four of its five starters scoring in double figures.

"It's been a great week for us," Sun coach Mike Thibault said.
"We had the third best road record last year and one of our goals
is to be the top two or three again."

Chamique Holdsclaw scored a game-high 25 points for the Mystics
(2-4). Rookie Alana Beard, who started at point guard for the
second straight game in place of the injured Tamicha Jackson,
chipped in 13 points.

Connecticut trailed by as many as 13 in the first half. But the
Sun tightened their defense, forcing Washington to rely on jump
shots.

"We allowed too many points in the paint in the first half,"
Douglas said. "After the first half, we had to build a wall in the
paint and force them to shoot outside."

Washington also collapsed defensively coming out of the break,
and Connecticut was quick to capitalize.

"In the first half, our defense's intensity was there,"
Holdsclaw said. "In the second half, we had a couple slip-ups, and
then they were able to make some great plays."

After being called for her third personal foul of the game for
bumping Sun point guard Debbie Black, Holdsclaw got a technical
foul with 9:22 remaining. Katie Douglas converted the free throw,
giving the Sun a 57-55 lead.

With four lead changes over the final 6:20, Palmer gave
Connecticut the lead for good on a driving layup, and Whalen added
a 3-pointer at 4:57, which sealed the win for Connecticut.
